  "title": "OneTrust (system) — 3pi-v2 Project Reference Article",
  "summary": "This article documents the OneTrust system within the 3pi-v2 project, detailing its role as the Third-Party Risk Management (TPRM) hub that coordinates data and workflow between OneTrust, Aravo, and downstream systems such as Salesforce. It explains how OneTrust enables automated risk classification, status propagation, and auditability through a tightly coupled API-driven integration. The piece provides a comprehensive view of the system’s origins, current operational footprint, and ongoing workstreams, while highlighting critical artifacts, stakeholders, and outstanding questions that shape future governance and delivery.\n\nThe OneTrust integration is a linchpin in the broader risk and compliance fabric, delivering automated triggers, field-level data quality controls (notably `customField1158`), and reliable retry semantics (e.g., a 2-hour cycle) to minimize manual interventions. Without it, downstream systems could diverge on TPI statuses, compromising auditability and timely remediation. The article maps upstream inputs (OneTrust TPRM data) to downstream outputs (Aravo and Salesforce status propagation), and places ownership and accountability within the McKinsey & Company risk program and its cyber/TPRM teams.\n\nCross-references to [[OneTrust (system)]], [[Aravo]], [[Salesforce]], and internal stakeholders are embedded throughout, creating a definitive, citable reference for engineers, risk managers, and program leadership.\n",
  "infobox": {
    "type": "system",
    "projects": ["3pi-v2"],
    "role": "API-enabled TPRM data synchronization and risk workflow gateway"
  },
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Overview",
      "content": "OneTrust, in the context of the 3pi-v2 program, serves as the primary TPRM system that anchors third-party risk assessment, review, and downstream data propagation. The system is positioned upstream of Aravo and Salesforce and acts as the authoritative source for compliance posture and supplier statuses that flow into downstream risk and procurement workflows. The core problem it solves is the friction between human review cycles and automated data movement across risk platforms, ensuring that status changes, comments, and risk signals are consistently reflected across the ecosystem. This reduces manual handoffs, accelerates remediation, and strengthens auditability across the vendor lifecycle.\n\nThree distinct capabilities anchor OneTrust’s role in the 3pi-v2 landscape: first, API-driven triggers and data export to downstream systems; second, data quality control around critical fields such as the TPI Comments field (customField1158) to ensure that approved or non-TPI decisions can be propagated without manual intervention; and third, automated retry and reconciliation logic that replays updates on fixed cadences (notably a 2-hour cycle) to guarantee eventual consistency. Evidence from the project communications shows explicit statements like: \"the pipeline retries every 2 hours automatically\" and references to the field `customField1158`, which embodies the operational gate for sync between OneTrust and downstream systems. Additionally, discussions around the API integration plan (Initiative #7658) and the BRD for the API connection highlight the explicit shift from manual, email-driven updates to a controlled, system-to-system workflow.\n\nIn architectural terms, OneTrust sits at the boundary between policy reviews and automated data propagation. The evidence highlights a contract-like flow: OneTrust identifies a compliance outcome, then Aravo auto-updates TPI flags and Salesforce consumes the resulting state changes. The design is reinforced by mentions of an API trigger and a concrete data contract, such as `supplier_is_false_positive` in the context of a de-duplication or false-positive handling flow. The relationship graph reveals that OneTrust is tightly coupled with multiple stakeholders, including McKinsey risk teams, product managers, and the broader third-party risk function, signaling a system that is both strategic and operationally critical to risk posture.\n\n[[OneTrust (system)]] is therefore a central node in the risk data fabric, with explicit interfaces to [[Aravo]] and [[Salesforce]] and a set of internal governance relationships that include named individuals such as Rijul Kalra and Deepti Zimmerman, among others. The evidence also points to organizational owners like McKinsey & Company and the Optimize/Third-Party Risk teams, underscoring the system’s strategic importance and cross-functional dependencies. The ongoing API integration program (Initiative #7658) signals a broader modernization effort that aims to standardize inter-system data movement and reduce dependence on email-driven processes.\n"
    },
    {
      "heading": "History & Context",
      "content": "The OneTrust integration narrative begins in the broader McKinsey risk program, with early indications of a shift away from manual third-party risk workflows toward a system-driven, auditable API-based pipeline. The evidence shows concrete milestones in early 2026, including references to a BRD for the API integration and the designation of OneTrust’s TPRM module as the focal point for vendor risk posture across the 3pi-v2 program. The origin of the effort is anchored by a set of conversations and email threads around February 2026 that formalized the initiative as Initiative #7658 - 3P Cyber - API Integration - BRD, signaling a strategic decision to standardize data movement between OneTrust and Aravo.\n\nA pivotal shift occurs in March 2026, when leadership and product teams map the target future state to the current state. On February 27, 2026, Pankaj Arora circulated a BRD and linked side-by-side comparisons of current versus future states, including Use Case 1 (TPIs vs non-TPI transitions) and Use Case 2 (non-TPI → TPI transitions). The emails emphasize a system-to-system trigger approach, moving away from manual notifications to automatic workflow initiation in Aravo and downstream systems. This period also marks the entry of dedicated PMs and team leads for the OneTrust integration, notably “Graham Holton” (PM) and “Tobias Dietrich” (TL) as discussed in internal synchronization in mid-March 2026, highlighting the governance and ownership mechanics that underpin the project’s momentum.\n\nThe historical narrative also reflects an evolution in data governance between OneTrust and Aravo. By March 10–12, 2026, communications describe the need to populate the TPI Comments field in OneTrust (customField1158) for multiple vendors. The repeated requests, including a March 11–12, 2026 sequence, show the systemic dependency on the TPI Comments field to enable automatic downstream processing, with explicit references to the impact on Salesforce synchronization and Aravo status propagation. The before state—manual updates via email and ticketing—was replaced by an automated API-driven workflow that captures changes, logs audit trails, and reconciles statuses across the risk stack.\n\nAdditionally, there is a notable thread about supplier deactivations and data parity across systems dating to June 2025, where deactivated suppliers in Aravo should propagate to OneTrust and vice versa. This historical thread underscores the pre-existing friction that motivated the API-driven integration, as evidenced by communications highlighting mismatches and the need to maintain consistency across Aravo and OneTrust. Taken together, the sequence from February to March 2026 marks the critical pivot from ad hoc, email-centric synchronization to a formal API-enabled partnership between OneTrust, Aravo, and downstream risk systems, anchored by governance from McKinsey risk leadership and the cyber risk program.\n"
    },
    {
      "heading": "Technical Details",
      "content": "The OneTrust system exposes a data contract and operational patterns that enable cross-system risk orchestration with Aravo and Salesforce. Central to this contract are concrete artifacts and interfaces that are repeatedly referenced in the evidence: the API-driven trigger mechanism, the critical field `customField1158` (TPI Comments) in OneTrust, and the downstream data flow into Aravo and Salesforce. The evidence also highlights a concrete API endpoint for vendor data exposure: `/api/v2/vendors`, which is the canonical target for up-stream pulls and for error remediation when required fields are missing. The data flow can be summarized as OneTrust → Aravo → Salesforce, with system-to-system triggers replacing manual email updates and tickets as the primary mechanism for state changes.\n\nFrom the evidence set, several artifacts stand out as explicit technical tokens in the integration design. First, `customField1158` is the TPI Comments field in OneTrust that the pipeline depends on to unlock downstream processing; it is repeatedly identified as the gating criterion for syncing results to Aravo and Salesforce. Second, the API surface is codified in references to `/api/v2/vendors`, indicating the endpoint scope used by the integration to surface vendor-level metadata for reconciliation and status propagation. Third, the integration discussion uses the term OneTrust TPRM module to denote the functional boundary that encapsulates vendor reviews, risk scoring, and final disposition flags that drive downstream state updates. Fourth, the field `supplier_is_false_positive` is introduced in the context of specific records requiring an additional knob for risk stance, indicating conditional logic in the data contract for false positives.\n\nOperationally, the deployment model shows a shift to a system-to-system trigger pattern and an automated 2-hour cycle for retrying failed sync attempts. The evidence cites phrases such as \"The pipeline retries every 2 hours automatically\" and describes a future state where Aravo auto-updates the TPI flag after confirmation, with an audit trail and a full system audit log in Aravo. Guardrails and vetting activities are explicitly mentioned as part of the automated workflow, signaling a robust control plane around risk decisions. The BRD for the API integration, Initiative #7658, documents the side-by-side comparisons of current (manual) versus future (automated) flows, including Use Case 1 and Use Case 2 mappings that define the end-to-end contracts and triggers. The combined artifact set—`customField1158`, `/api/v2/vendors`, `supplier_is_false_positive`, OneTrust TPRM module, and the API integration BRD—constitutes the technical backbone of the OneTrust integration in 3pi-v2.\n\nIn deployment terms, the integration is described as system-to-system, with Aravo and Salesforce receiving status changes via API-driven triggers rather than email messages. The evidence also notes that some mismatches stem from deactivated suppliers in Aravo and their reflection in OneTrust, a scenario that the API integration aims to resolve through automatic synchronization and auditability. The architecture rests on a triad of components: OneTrust (system) for data governance and gating of downstream updates, Aravo for risk flagging and governance workflow, and Salesforce for customer-facing risk views and opportunity-level alignment. The practical outcome is a more deterministic and auditable risk posture across the vendor lifecycle, with explicit triggers, contracts, data contracts, and data schemas enabling consistent state propagation across the ecosystem.\n"
    },
    {
      "heading": "Key Relationships",
      "content": "The OneTrust integration is a cross-functional, multi-stakeholder effort that spans the OneTrust system, the Aravo risk platform, and downstream systems like Salesforce, backed by McKinsey risk program leadership and cyber risk specialists. At a human governance level, the graph Neighborhood identifies several named individuals and organizational units that participate in the relationship map. McKinsey & Company (org_unit) is a central governance axis, described as a primary partner that works with OneTrust on third-party risk and compliance workflows across the project surface. The OneTrust TPRM module itself serves as a core system that interfaces with Aravo and downstream consumers, acting as the gatekeeper for TPI status changes and field-level data required for downstream processing.\n\nKey individuals and teams connected to the OneTrust system include Rijul Kalra (person) and Parth Patel (person), who appear as core stakeholders in the risk workflow discussions and in the governance of the 3pi-v2 integration. Deepti Zimmerman (person) is referenced repeatedly in emails as a primary owner or coordinator for the risk strategy and optimization effort, and tends to be involved in communications about OneTrust- to-Aravo data flow and the handling of TPI cases. The Product Manager (person) and the Teams (system) entities in the graph connect product leadership and orchestration layers to the technical implementation, ensuring that the interface semantics and data contracts align with operational needs. Other human actors in the evidence include Tendayi Owens, Alexandra Rada, and Pankaj Arora, who appear in the thread around API integration and the BRD, marking cross-functional collaboration across risk, cyber, and optimization units.\n\nFrom the system perspective, Aravo and Salesforce are critical downstream systems that participate in the data propagation cycle, with OHD (office of head of data) mentioned as a workflow trigger recipient for approvals and changes. The evidence includes multiple references to the flow of information and control: OneTrust TPRM module ↔ Aravo (system-to-system trigger) ↔ Salesforce (data consumer); and the broader governance interfaces with McKinsey’s Third Party Risk Strategy & Cyber Risk team, including “Graham Holton” (PM) and “Tobias Dietrich” (TL), who are explicitly named in the March 12, 2026, correspondence. The relationships are further reinforced by the presence of Optimize Solutions (document) and the broader risk program, which denotes a cross-entity collaboration pattern that binds the OneTrust system to a web of organizational units, product teams, and risk functions. In sum, the OneTrust integration is a web of six or more concrete connections: [[McKinsey & Company (org_unit)]], [[OneTrust (system)]], [[Aravo (system)]], [[Salesforce (system)]], [[Rijul Kalra]] (person), [[Deepti Zimmerman]] (person), [[Parth Patel]] (person), [[Graham Holton]] (person), [[Tobias Dietrich]] (person), [[Product Manager]] (role), and [[Optimize Solutions]] (document).\n"
    },
    {
      "heading": "Current Status",
      "content": "As of the most recent evidence, the OneTrust integration is in active operational mode with multiple concurrent workstreams and a known incident trajectory tied to data quality gates in OneTrust. The project explicitly aligns around Initiative #7658 (3P Cyber - API Integration - BRD), with ongoing work to operationalize the API-driven data pipeline between OneTrust and Aravo, and to propagate updated risk state to Salesforce. Evidence indicates that the API integration work has progressed toward system-to-system triggers and that a number of vendors have reached a stable state, while a subset remains blocked by missing `customField1158` values.\n\nTwo active workstreams are prominent in the evidence: first, the API integration BRD implementation and its enforcement in ongoing development and testing cycles; second, the remediation of blocked vendor records stemming from missing tpi_comments in OneTrust (customField1158). The March 11–12, 2026, email threads document a concrete incident class: roughly 30 TPI records were stuck in the OneTrust → Salesforce/Aravo sync path due to the absence of TPI Comments, with 8 remaining as of the latest update and a stated delivery constraint of a 2-hour retry cadence. The threads also reveal a leadership model for this work, naming McKinsey stakeholder anchors and the AR/OneTrust integration team’s plan to enable automatic downstream flow once the missing field is populated.\n\nRecent communications also reflect a broader governance and risk-management context. The Nigeria IA likely triggered deactivation and reactivation discussions in 2025, evidenced by the March 10–13, 2026 exchanges that describe how the API integration will resolve mismatches across deactivated vendors, and the transition away from manual remediation to automated reconciliation and audit trails in Aravo and OneTrust. Overall, the current state exhibits a working, API-enabled pipeline with clearly identified blockers around `customField1158` and a defined cadence for retries, while maintaining a high-level commitment to the automation and governance improvements described in the BRD and Use Case analyses.\n"
    },
    {
      "heading": "Open Questions",
      "content": "The most salient unresolved items center on operational readiness, timing, and governance alignment for the OneTrust integration. First, the timeline for populating the TPI Comments field (customField1158) for the remaining 8 vendors remains [inferred] from March 11–12, 2026 communications, and a concrete date for field population and subsequent automatic syncing to Aravo/Salesforce is not explicitly committed in the provided evidence. Second, there is an ongoing need to confirm ownership boundaries for the automated workflow adjustments—specifically, whether OneTrust side or Aravo side should own certain post-change actions (e.g., final review vs. automatic flagging) as described in the Use Case 2 discussions and the side-by-side BRD comparison. Third, the historical misalignment observed in June 2025 between deactivated suppliers in Aravo and OneTrust poses a data integrity risk that requires an explicit reconciliation plan, governance cadence, and auditability enhancements to ensure parity across platforms.\n\nOther open questions include the precise field-level schemas for downstream Salesforce representations of TPI status and how failures in the 2-hour retry loop are surfaced and remediated. There is also a question about how the “supplier_is_false_positive” flag should be treated in the automated workflow and under what conditions it should trigger alternative reconciliation flows. Finally, with the API integration nearing production readiness, it remains to be verified whether the BRD’s guardrails, vetting steps, and Full system audit log in Aravo meet the organization’s audit requirements without introducing new latency in risk decision cycles. Addressing these items will close the evidentiary gaps and finalize the governance and technical readiness of OneTrust as the central TPRM hub in the 3pi-v2 architecture."
    }
  ],
